{"id":14881053,"mediaExerciseId":"ff990349-44be-481c-b92a-0087b3ac2177","exerciseName":"4","chapterName":"7","chapterTitle":"Interest Rates and Bond Valuation","groupId":612313,"groupTitle":"Questions and Problems","isPremium":true,"sectionName":null,"sectionTitle":null,"pageNumber":233,"solutions":[{"id":5990801,"modifiedOn":"2021-01-01T00:00:00.000000","steps":[{"columns":[{"text":"In this task, we have **to calculate the yield to maturity of the Japanese company.**","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":1},{"columns":[{"text":"Let's write down the formula for the bond price and calculate all the items inside.\n\n$$\\text{Price}=\\dfrac{\\text{C}}{\\left(1+\\text{YTM}\\right)}+\\dfrac{\\text{C}}{\\left(1+\\text{YTM}\\right)^\\text{2}}+...+\\dfrac{\\text{C}+\\text{P}}{\\left(1+\\text{YTM}\\right)^\\text{n}}$$\n\n$C$-coupon of the bond \n\n$YTM$-yield to maturity\n\n$P$-par value\n\n$n$-time","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":2},{"columns":[{"text":"Let's first calculate the coupon bond.\n\n\n$$\\begin{aligned}\n\\text{Coupon value}&=\\text{par value}\\times\\text{coupon rate}\\\\\n\\\\\n&=\\$100,000\\times3.4\\%\\\\\n\\\\\n&=\\boxed{\\$3,400}\n\\end{aligned}$$\n \nThe coupon bond is \\$3,400, and it is a fixed amount every year.","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":68,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/07/1f1a6bd6ad5e551078993790ce7ba08d/db40adbdc371b22bdda3e36581c30b58/lateximg_large.png","width":996},"regular":{"height":34,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/07/1f1a6bd6ad5e551078993790ce7ba08d/db40adbdc371b22bdda3e36581c30b58/lateximg.png","width":499}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":3},{"columns":[{"text":"Now, let's calculate the current value of the bond. In the exercise is written that it is 105.34\\% of the par value. \n\n$$\\begin{aligned}\n\\text{Current Calue}&=105.43\\%\\times\\$100,000\\\\[15pt]\n&=\\boxed{\\$105,430}\n\\end{aligned}$$\n\nThe current value of the bond is \\$105,430.","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":328,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/07/1f1a6bd6ad5e551078993790ce7ba08d/237f2ad245065836cc5753674d60b039/lateximg_large.png","width":997},"regular":{"height":166,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/07/1f1a6bd6ad5e551078993790ce7ba08d/237f2ad245065836cc5753674d60b039/lateximg.png","width":498}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":4},{"columns":[{"text":"Now, we have all the necessary data, and let's calculate the yield to maturity.\n\n$$\\$105,430=\\dfrac{\\$3,400}{\\left(1+\\text{YTM}\\right)}+\\dfrac{\\$3,400}{\\left(1+\\text{YTM}\\right)^\\text{2}}+...+\\dfrac{\\$3,400+\\$100,000}{\\left(1+\\text{YTM}\\right)^\\text{16}}$$\n","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":343,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/07/1f1a6bd6ad5e551078993790ce7ba08d/b38a0e7292873e0df6d97984281ee639/lateximg_large.png","width":831},"regular":{"height":173,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/07/1f1a6bd6ad5e551078993790ce7ba08d/b38a0e7292873e0df6d97984281ee639/lateximg.png","width":417}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":5},{"columns":[{"text":"We can classify **yield to maturity** as a return rate. More specifically, yield to maturity is what an investor will earn if he holds the bond until the maturity date when the issuer pays back all the promised interest payments and the amount of the debt written in the contract (principal). We can say that this is a nominal interest rate at the annual level. The best way to calculate yield to maturity is to use a financial calculator.\n\nIt is not the same as the coupon rate. Coupon rates are determined by the entity that issues a bond. The coupon value will be the same for every future payment. So it is a fixed amount.","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":287,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/07/1f1a6bd6ad5e551078993790ce7ba08d/cfeb374ef36b9d844cb0814430ebb7c5/lateximg_large.png","width":997},"regular":{"height":145,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/07/1f1a6bd6ad5e551078993790ce7ba08d/cfeb374ef36b9d844cb0814430ebb7c5/lateximg.png","width":499}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":6},{"columns":[{"text":"If we use Spreadsheets or a financial calculator, we can get that the yield to maturity is **2.9687\\%.**","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":138,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/07/1f1a6bd6ad5e551078993790ce7ba08d/4b77ca4fd881ca276e0d776531a69807/lateximg_large.png","width":993},"regular":{"height":71,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/07/1f1a6bd6ad5e551078993790ce7ba08d/4b77ca4fd881ca276e0d776531a69807/lateximg.png","width":497}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":7}],"rating":0,"solutionUuid":"3fec4ecf-e66c-4806-b1ae-d86e6f58e34a","editorVersion":2,"answeredOn":null,"ratingCount":null,"solutionOrder":null,"totalSteps":7}],"textbook":{"authors":"Bradford D. Jordan, Randolph W. Westerfield, Stephen A. Ross","imageUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/textbook_covers/tmpm0p82b7h","imageThumbnailUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/cache/d1/d3/d1d34d106dd29dd2e71be582412ef59d.jpg","id":34320,"isbn":"9781259918957","isPremium":true,"title":"Fundamentals of Corporate Finance","edition":"12th Edition","verifiedSolutionCount":1217,"shouldBeIndexableForSeo":true,"modified":1665448474394,"active":true,"publisher":"McGraw-Hill Education","mainTextbookIsbn":null,"subjects":{"level1":["Social Science"],"level2":["Economics"],"level3":["Finance"]}},"nextExercises":[{"id":14881054,"exerciseName":"5","pa